An agreement, dated 14th May 1507, between Archbishop Blacader and “Thomas Tayt, burgess of Ayr,'’ is of considerable interest. By this document the burgess contracts to sell to the prelato “twelve fuderis* of lead,” at the price of 18 pounds Scots for each “ fuder,'’ under certain conditions as to delivery. It was probably destined for the south transept of the Cathedral, which the Archbishop began, but did not live to complete. The terms of the option given to the lead-merchant to dclivcr either at the burgh of Renfrew, or at the shallow (eodum) of Govan, if his ship could be conveniently brought up to the latter place, are curicus as showing the difficult access by water to the city at this period. On the 24th J anu- ary 1513, an incidental notice of the provost deputo, John Schaw, who, with Thomas Law and William Baxter, bailies, held a court in “pretorio burgi,'' confirms the tradition that the Provost of Glasgow was slain at Flodden a few months before.
